In economics, history offers little clue as to time frame.
After the first interest rate hike, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness to raise interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That’s why U.S. central bank officials have so strongly accentuated the fact that investors should not focus on when the interest rate starts to rise, but on the trajectory of the time it takes to normalize.
In fact, there are multiple variables in the game.
However, in the end, market players might find that all the turmoil associated with the interest rate increase has been exaggerated.
“The first interest rate increase decided by the Fed after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a sign of the ‘cheap money’ era,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels to be the seismic shock that everyone seems to be afraid of.
However, it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Below we present how some sectors of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation the market has faced in recent months, anticipating interest rate hikes can volatilize things for a while.
But at the moment of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency for capital returns to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first rise, which may reflect the monetary policy phase-out again,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what will happen after the Fed’s rises.
Specifically, in the last 35 years, the market has risen sharply - by about 14 percent - heading for an increase in the interest rate, quite invariable in the period of 250 days after (average rise of 2.6%) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six years.
Deutsche said the impact on stocks tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate hike cycle and benefits are starting to decline.
The recession is a reality of economic life but an increase in the interest rate often contributes to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, the gross domestic product will approach its historic low point for an increase in the Fed’s interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Even though the value was 3.6% in the second quarter of 2015, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter reaching just 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Rising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question “if this time it’s different,” Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing all year for a growth decision by the Fed, all eyes being on this week’s meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an interest rate increase on the occasion of this meeting, futures trading indicates a probability of only 25%.
“In our study after 1950, all interest rate cycles so far have been in a super-cycle of profit growth, with GDP eclipsing pre-recession peaks very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
