The main difference is that the impact is faster in the case of bonds than in the case of stocks when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, it appears that the benefits change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate hike cycle, the yield of bonds is immediately declining,” Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab’s strategies are of the opinion that these interest rate increases will bring yields closer between short-term and long-term bonds, flattening the curve.
