On the other hand, Bank Transylvania’s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of clients with loans in francs due to second successive reductions: the balance was reduced with the value of risk and management commissions paid by the client, then an additional reduction of 22.5 % was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to how much they paid monthly equivalent in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Benefit
The main advantage of leu loans in CHF is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future increases in the franc, and the repayment of the loan will be made in the currency in which he collects his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no reassessment of the property, no further guarantees are required and another proof of income.
Practically, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the credit and there will be no additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer a discount on the monthly rate, compared to how much customers paid before the conversion, the equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first years is formed more of the interest, and the customer pays back very little of the principal.
Bancpost’s offer with very low interest rates in the first three years seems to be advantageous for customers.
It is unclear how this will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be greater than 3.25%, so overall, and the cost reduction is lower.
