We don't need to go around the world five times a year if it doesn't help.
In Bach's time there were no world tournaments.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were people who worked, who were artists and not commercial representatives.
For me, organizing concerts, festivals, tours, releasing albums, all are formidable, extraordinary, but as long as they are done in the service of music.
If not, we are in a system where creativity suffers, no longer has freedom.
To illustrate this phenomenon, David Grimal gave an example to Romanian products before and after accession to the European Union: "In Romania, before entering the EU, you had good vegetables and meat".
In order to enter the EU, you had to adopt sanitary laws that are not good for vegetables and meat.
Production and agriculture are at the service of supermarkets, as is the case in France.
With music the same thing happens, it's the same logic.
Les Dissonances make reds may not be very nice, but when you cut them, they are real reds.
In an ideal world, this music should go back to the center and the institutions and industries that manage this system should understand that music does not need to be sold, but needs to be shared, and this can be done starting with educational policy.
"If we consider - as do Koreans, Chinese, Japanese - that Western music is one of the most beautiful things of humanity, we would reintroduce its learning in school, we would reintroduce the concerts on television and through this education we would no longer need to sell musical byproducts," Grimal said.
Certainly, there are things in classical music education that remain very communist, that everywhere, is something very militarized.
It depends on this discipline whether we compare a musician with a soldier, or whether we form a musician who will play an instrument, being, first of all, a musician.
We are talking about a completely different education, if we want to train a soldier (this education) it must be in a way, if we want to train a musician, it is completely different.
In your opinion, what is more dangerous, a soldier or a musician?” the French artist asks with a smile.
Grimal shows that, for artists, the reward of another way of making music comes precisely from overcoming this status of "soldier", overcoming what "they think are their limits": "Musicians discover at some point that they are not soldiers, and therefore after the concert there are smiling people".
David Grimal spoke about his musical project and his vision of music and the artist at the "Festival of Ideas", a discussion with the public organized at the George Enescu International Festival by the Aspen Romania Institute.
Profile of David Grimal
After attending the Conservatoire National Supérieur de Musique in Paris under the guidance of Regis Pasquier, during which time he received advice and encouragement from renowned artists such as Schlomo Mintz and Isaac Stern, David Grimal studied for a year at the Ecole des Sciences Politiques in Paris before meeting with Philippe Hirshor.
David Grimal has an international career as a solo violinist, along which he has performed regularly in the last 20 years, as well as in the main classical music scenes of the world and with prestigious orchestras such as Orchestre de Paris, Orchestre Philharmonique de Radio France, Russian National Orchestra, Orchestre National de Lyon, Orchestre Philernik of Lyon, Chamber New Europe.
