At the most anticipated meeting in recent years, policymakers within the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduras mahogany table to decide if it’s time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at the end of the central bank’s meeting room, will be a mural of the United States.
The map is intended to remind that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed’s president, and her colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank has received a double task from Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the U.S. and maintain price stability.
But since the big economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is an unwritten third task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in an overly difficult-to-anticipate decision to be announced Tuesday, which will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be debated by the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect from late 2008.
Even though most of the data indicates a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious about adding volatility by increasing the benchmark rate for federal funds — even just a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues that will follow,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were to look for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the world market is enough to give them an argument to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the decision the Fed will make, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
Approximately half of recent Bloomberg economists predicted an interest rate hike this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a fall in the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers would attenuate the blow by promising that it would take a long time until the next rise.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16.599.85.
The boom was triggered by expectations that Fed decision makers will keep the interest rate steady this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising if the Fed were to raise the interest rate right now,” Lonski said.
If the Fed’s decision makers did so, “they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets.”
Other experts said an interest rate hike would calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed about to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected an increase in the interest rate this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Salary gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, the Fed’s decision makers said a key reason was the temporary effect of oil prices falling sharply.
The economy “may be able to cope with higher rates and needs them given the labor market tension,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began fibrillating at the end of this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell by 16% below its record high in May, as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would bring down global growth.
The market fell somewhat this month, with the Dow index now about 10% below its peak in May.
For Fed decision makers, market turmoil is added to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate hike.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and the news of the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be more firm in the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a researcher with experience at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former official Fed.
Now, he expects that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the US economy and they have almost no data to base on subsequent events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so practically it should not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank’s influence has been huge.
President Ben S. Bernanke’s mere allusion in 2013 that the Fed could “narrow” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, it is expected that Fed officials will not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the global economy.
His decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy department at wellness management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., said this month that “the Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to economic bases.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the interest rate hike, gave as an example the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that has affected Asia has led the Fed to reduce the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the implications with limited identification for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials returned to their respective declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate commission.
The last turbulent period does not rise far at that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to get into the situation of fearing an interest rate rise because markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take action prematurely.
