Weight-loss surgery could be useful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be sustained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those following non-surgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Operations for weight loss, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of measurement of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range of 18.5-24.9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data gathered after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery – gastric bypass and gastrectomy in the sleeve – in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI in people who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments for diabetes remained nearly at the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes cured completely at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes completely cured only 1% and partially cured only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at about 8%.
But this improved “glycemic control” – reflected by improved levels of hemoglobin A1c – did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the group with gastrectomy in the sleeve, the group with bypass surgery lost more weight (18.7 vs 14.2 kg), recorded more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 vs 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 vs 2.1 %).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on high-weight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, from the University of Arizona, Phoenix School of Medicine.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic look for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
“This is where this work is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,” without the increased risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking the weight seriously when the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long to urge people to take this issue seriously,” she said.
I think once they have accumulated these genetic changes that have shortened their bodies by predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it’s extremely difficult to get back to normal.
