Four times the number of children who have ingested hand detergent in the last 4 years
According to the Georgia Anti-Poison Center, U.S. anti-poison centers have reported an increase of about 400% since 2010 in the number of children under 12 who swallowed high-alcohol hand detergent.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Anti-Poison Center in Georgia, cases of hand detergent intake in children under the age of 12 reported at anti-poison centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children have more frequent access to these products and, unfortunately, a percentage of them reach the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said some children intentionally drink detergent and others do so to impress their friends or to respond to challenges on social networks.
On YouTube you can watch movies that show teenagers how they drink detergent to create cheap drinks.
It turns out that teenagers mixed the mouthwash detergent with alcohol to get a hotter drink.
Younger children can be attracted to the attractive smell of detergent.
“A child doesn’t think he’s hurting them,” Lopez says.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergent) are the perfumed ones.
Hand detergents with a aroma of strawberries, grapes, orange are the most attractive for children.
Hand detergent contains about 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few swallows can cause alcohol poisoning.
“It’s very concentrated alcohol,” said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poison center at the University Hospital of Kansas, to the Kansas City Fox Channel 4.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones get to them, this is a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four strawberry-scented hand detergent sprays at school, reached the emergency room to receive treatment.
She had alcoholemia 179 times the threshold at which an adult is legally considered under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah moaned and could not walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage as the girl fell and hit her head due to alcohol, Ritchey said.
“It was frightening,” Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah’s mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal to him.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use non-alcoholic damp products or napkins and not to leave the detergent at the fingertips of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand detergent containing an undeclared toxic ingredient.
The health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, specified as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in northern New York plotted to poison their “bad” teacher by “putting antibacterial products in the classroom,” according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand detergent and banned it in her classroom.
Police deemed the plan "insignificant" and referred the disciplinary issue to the school inspectorate.
