FriendsFest: the comedy series that taught us important lessons about friendship between men
The absence of similar characters in the series is obvious, given that the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, with suicide rates among young men peaking in the last 15 years.
In 2013, suicide was the leading cause of death in men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more common in men than in women.
In an attempt to address the problem, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, wishing to question the culture that prevents men from asking for help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the struggle for the success of this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends “with a healthy mood,” his chances of recovery are doubled.
Likewise, for people who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends halve the likelihood of developing mental disorders.
Of course, in order for friendship to have effect, it must first be accessible.
In this age of communication dominated by social networks, where the emphasis is on style rather than substance, the immediate character of the response often takes precedence over contact with meaning.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and successful, even if in reality isolation is the one that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values—our inner desire for personal development and friendship—that profoundly affect our mental health.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money doesn’t even buy happiness.
The beauty of the Friends series was that it drew attention to this idea.
The characters were not defined by the job but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humour of Joey and Chandler’s frequent hugs, the moments they watch football in comfortable armchairs, and Ross’s passion for Rachel came from the fact that it is known that men can associate with this situation, even if they often refrain from fully exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: “My role of listening to people who are suicidal and depressed has shown how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference.”
Often, people who call us do not feel able to talk to friends.
The old saying to handle yourself alone is strong, as is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you talk openly about problems.
Friends is one of the series that comes to mind when I try to offer several long-term psychological adaptation mechanisms.
The series highlighted the little moments of friendship between men.
As much as objective, external intervention, through the phone, helps people who arrive in times of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
So, if you are attending this weekend at FriendsFest hosted by Comedy Central, with the full playback of the filming plates to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends to a coffee in Central Perk.
Or, better yet, if you see someone alone at Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what a difference your friendship could make.
